export const batch159 = {
  "noise.json": {
    base: { id: "noise", title: "Noise", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781605994898 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Outside forces shape your worst calls",
        text: "Every day, the world throws signals at us from every direction. The eyes see, the ears hear, the skin feels, the tongue tastes, the nose smells, and the brain has to sort all of it. That nonstop stream is the noise inside which every choice is made. Most of it has nothing to do with the actual problem in front of you. That mismatch is what researchers mean when they say there is noise in a decision.\n\nDaniel Kahneman describes noise as the unwanted chatter that creeps into a person's reasoning. A short story shows how it works.\n\nA respected hiring manager named Sarah had three candidates to interview for one important job. The first, Emily, came in early in the morning. Sarah had spilled coffee on her favorite shirt and felt grumpy. The second, David, came in after lunch. Sarah had shared a good meal with coworkers and felt sunny. The third, Michael, came in late in the afternoon. Sarah was tired and could not stay focused, and her mind kept drifting to her evening plans, so she missed key parts of his background.\n\nAfter the interviews, Sarah looked at her notes and picked David. The reasons behind her pick, the spilled coffee, the good lunch, the long afternoon, had nothing to do with the job. They were noise, and noise drove her choice.\n\nLearning how your mind fools you is the first step toward better calls.\n\nMost people assume they would never fall for such tricks, yet they already have. Noise touches every choice, from the small daily ones to the ones that change a life. Once you accept that noise is real and learn how it works, it can become a tool rather than a trap.\n\nReady to leave poor choices behind? This summary will help you spot noise and start making sharper calls."
      },
      {
        title: "Random errors hide inside every system",
        text: "Every day, people make many calls that ripple into the lives of others. Hidden errors in judgment pop up in places most of us never think to look.\n\nInside the justice system, people who commit the same crime often walk away with very different sentences. In the 1970s, Judge Marvin Frankel, a lawyer who cared deeply about human rights, called attention to the problem. He compared the situation to shuffling a deck of cards with real lives on the line.\n\nResearchers ran studies where judges were asked to sentence fictional cases. The sentences varied wildly from judge to judge. Sometimes the panel could not even agree on whether prison was the right call. The swing in punishment felt like a Whack-a-Mole game where the mallet landed with the weight of a feather one moment and a brick the next.\n\nHunger, local sports scores, and even the weather have all been shown to nudge how judges rule. Studies suggest that people focus better and decide more accurately on cloudy days than on bright sunny ones.\n\nThe same kind of unwanted variation shows up in business and costs real money. One insurance firm checked whether different underwriters priced the same cases similarly. The audit found a fifty-five percent gap between the lowest and highest numbers, and a forty-three percent gap among claims adjusters.\n\nThat kind of drift can drain hundreds of millions of dollars from a company. The lesson is clear. Stripping noise out of a company's decisions saves money and treats customers more fairly.\n\nResearchers also turned up a second pattern they call the illusion of agreement. Picture a group of traders asked to value one stock. Each person writes down a number, and every number is different. If a firm learned that its investors disagreed by forty-one percent when pricing the same asset, it would think twice before taking their word for it.\n\nMost people do not realize how much they disagree. They assume everyone sees the same picture, yet everyone is reading a different book. Scientists call the habit naive realism.\n\nEach person's view of the world is as unique as a fingerprint, yet people treat their own view as if it were universal.\n\nNoise slips into hospitals, courtrooms, and boardrooms. Cleaning it out is one of the cheapest ways to improve the choices that shape our lives."
      },
      {
        title: "Algorithms bring calmer judgment to the bench",
        text: "Let us head back to the courts for a moment. In 2018, a research team led by Sendhil Mullainathan trained a computer model to predict whether a defendant would flee before trial. They fed the system data from about 760,000 real bail hearings. The model looked at the current charge, the defendant's record, and past failures to appear in court. It left out almost all personal details, keeping only age.\n\nThe algorithm beat the human judges in several ways. It cut crime rates by up to twenty-four percent. It lowered the number of people held in jail by up to forty-two percent. It flagged high-risk defendants more sharply.\n\nHuman judges, in contrast, swung between being soft and strict, and their judgments bounced around from case to case. The algorithm showed less racial bias than the judges who were sentencing in court. The team could even tweak the model's settings to push for fairer outcomes across racial groups.\n\nIn a separate test inside a large tech company, an algorithm screened resumes better than human reviewers. The software pulled in a more diverse pool of candidates.\n\nRules and algorithms beat people because they do not have moods, cravings, or grudges, and they spot patterns that tired eyes miss. Still, not every algorithm plays fair. Some models bake in the same racial and gender gaps that hurt people in the first place.\n\nA well-trained machine can be more accurate and more even-handed than a tired human. The catch is the training. Sloppy training produces sloppy machines.\n\nEven with all those gains, many professionals still lean on human judgment. Doctors diagnosing illness, recruiters picking hires, and coaches building sports teams often trust people over machines.\n\nKahneman notes that most people are not against algorithms. They give them a fair shot, then turn away after the first mistake. That hunger for perfection keeps humans in the loop even when the machines are already better. The preference for the human touch runs deep and will only fade when algorithms become almost flawless.\n\nStill, there are pieces of the algorithm world that humans can borrow, such as simple rules and clean routines.\n\nA chatbot called DoNotPay helped more than 160,000 people in the UK and the US overturn parking tickets, a small sign that software can offer legal help at a fraction of the cost of a lawyer."
      },
      {
        title: "Crowds go silent when peers lean in",
        text: "One person's judgment can already drift, and groups make the drift worse. Small shifts in how a meeting runs, such as who speaks first or how loud they speak, can swing the final call by a wide margin.\n\nGroupthink nudges people to hide their doubts so the team can stay friendly, and that pressure weakens the group's final answer.\n\nInformation cascades offer a clear example. The first opinion in a room pulls the next ones behind it. A snowball forms when one idea grabs the floor early, and the group ends up at a confident but wrong answer.\n\nSociologist Matthew Salganik and his coauthors showed how cascades play out in music downloads. When people saw how many of their peers had already downloaded a song, they were more likely to download it too.\n\nThe same pattern shows up in politics and in online comment threads, where an early burst of support keeps feeding itself. It is proof that one loud voice can tip a group's outcome.\n\nWhere there is judgment, there is noise, and usually more of it than people expect.\n\nInformation cascades grow when people anchor their choice on someone else's view instead of their own. Imagine a hiring panel. If the first speaker backs a certain candidate, the rest of the room may fall in line even if they had different ideas. The result can look like agreement, but it is not the wisdom of the group.\n\nA crowd is only wise when its members think on their own. Even a small dose of social pressure can turn independent thinkers into a herd that mirrors the loudest voice. When people decide on their own, their mistakes tend to cancel out, and the group answer gets closer to the truth. The more variety in the room, the better.\n\nSo when you want a second opinion, ask people one at a time and keep their answers private. Some researchers warn that group brainstorming can push people toward conformity and crush new ideas. An alternative is the Delphi method, which gathers anonymous input over several rounds so social pressure cannot bend the answers."
      },
      {
        title: "Choose judges who judge well",
        text: "Algorithms are not always the right replacement for human thinking. For your team to do well, you need people who are good at making hard calls. Since the goal is to lower bias, look for decision makers who are well-trained, smart, and open-minded enough to keep learning.\n\nTraining and experience set the floor for how much you can trust a specialist. Two kinds of experts exist. There are true experts with a verified track record, and there are respect-experts whose credibility comes from how their peers view them. You can spot a respect-expert through shared habits, years in the field, and steady confidence. Experience matters in most fields, though some problems call for someone with formal training, the right degrees, and the oversight of a professional body.\n\nPick a specialist whose experience you can verify. Smart decision makers also need raw brainpower. General mental ability, or GMA, links to strong performance in many areas, from job reviews to grades. You can ask candidates to take a short GMA test during hiring. The test has its critics, but its power to predict success is strong, especially in roles that demand complex thinking.\n\nGMA tests help when every candidate looks qualified on paper. Still, GMA has limits. It is not practical to test everyone, and high scorers can talk a great game without being truly skilled. Finding real experts means looking at more than test scores.\n\nCognitive style matters too. Reflective thinkers who slow down, weigh the evidence, and stay open to new facts tend to make better calls. A strong decision maker hunts for evidence that runs against the preferred answer and only commits once the picture is clear.\n\nThe best decision makers may not look like the loud leader in the room. They welcome counterarguments, watch for their own errors, and only get firm once the debate is done.\n\nWhen you need to pick whose advice to take, follow a simple path. If you know nothing about a candidate's track record, lean on the smartest one in the room. When two candidates are equally sharp, choose the most open-minded. If you must pick between a deep specialist and a thoughtful, curious generalist, bet on the latter."
      },
      {
        title: "Letting go of bias is hard but necessary",
        text: "When biases color the way you think, you end up making calls from incomplete or twisted information. That skewed view leads to bad choices, unfair treatment, and harm at work and at home.\n\nWhether you make a decision once or a hundred times, your aim should be the same. Cut both bias and noise. Two main ways to clean up your judgment are corrective and preventive.\n\nCorrective debiasing fixes calls after the fact. It means revisiting past decisions, giving feedback to the people who made them, and tightening the process so the same mistake is less likely next time.\n\nPreventive debiasing stops bias from getting a foothold in the first place. It usually runs on two tracks. One track watches decisions in real time and steps in when bias shows up. The other teaches decision makers to spot their own blind spots before they act.\n\nTeaching people to shed bias is hard, yet researchers have found tools that help. Interactive games and short media lessons work surprisingly well for adults. These methods show people the patterns behind their errors, give feedback on specific slips, and train them to act differently next time.\n\nA decision observer can also guard a team against bias. The observer can be anyone who knows the subject well. The most common setup uses a supervisor who watches how a proposal comes together, a team member assigned as a bias buster, or an outside facilitator who brings a neutral view.\n\nThat outside voice can flag blind spots and offer fresh feedback. Working with a decision observer helps a team weigh options through clear analysis rather than gut feel. It also makes the process more transparent and harder to bend toward a personal agenda.\n\nDecision observers need training and the right tools. A checklist of common biases, tailored to the decision at hand, gives them a concrete way to scan the room. Train the observer to use the checklist well and to give feedback that decision makers can actually use."
      },
      {
        title: "Final thoughts",
        text: "Noise is a strange idea with a lot to teach about how people choose. It asks us to admit that we are wrong sometimes and to look inward for a fix.\n\nNoise is not always outside us. Sometimes it lives inside our own heads. It can be the quiet worry that tips a small choice, or the loud echo of a past failure that freezes us when we need to act. Noise takes as many shapes as the human mind, and each shape nudges a decision in its own way.\n\nSo how do you make peace with noise? One way is to treat it as a mirror. Instead of letting it steer you without your noticing, you can name the small factors at play and ask why they pull you. That kind of reflection makes you more aware and more in charge.\n\nNoise can also push you to seek out views that are not your own. A wider set of perspectives makes the final call stronger, and that diversity turns noise into a doorway to open thinking and inclusion.\n\nAccepting that you are easily distracted can make you gentler with yourself and with others.\n\nHere is a small set of habits to try. Do not beat yourself up over a call that went wrong. Treat it as a lesson. Be willing to suspect that your first instinct is being pulled by noise. When you face a choice, ask whether one bias is bending the picture, and remember that several quiet biases often gang up. Finally, give yourself credit for any small step you make toward a cleaner decision."
      }
    ]
  },
  "nothing-to-envy.json": {
    base: { id: "nothing-to-envy", title: "Nothing to Envy", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781681152563 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "How US meddling carved Korea in two",
        text: "Before the Second World War and the fall of the Japanese Empire, the Korean peninsula was a small Japanese colony with little global weight. Once the war ended, the United States and the Soviet Union both turned their eyes on this quiet stretch of land, each wanting to spread its own brand of politics. The US worried that the USSR might use Korea as a stepping stone toward Japan, so it offered the Soviets the northern half as a temporary trust and kept the southern half for itself.\n\nThe line drawn across the country fell on the thirty-eighth parallel, and the Korean people had no voice in the matter. They had gone from one foreign power, Japan, to two rival ones, the US and the USSR.\n\nThe split between North and South Korea was a stroke of the pen. Nothing in Korean history had marked that border as special.\n\nIn the north, Kim Il-sung rose to lead the new Democratic People's Republic of Korea. In the south, Syngman Rhee took charge of the Republic of Korea. Two years later, in 1950, both halves claimed the whole peninsula. That clash of claims lit the fuse for the Korean War. On June 25, Kim Il-sung launched a surprise attack on the south and seized Seoul, the capital. Soviet tanks rolled at the front of the invasion.\n\nSeveral countries, including the United States and fifteen others, rushed to South Korea's defense. Together, they pushed Kim Il-sung's forces back. At the same time, Chinese troops moved in to support the North.\n\nThis summary opens a window onto life in North Korea through the eyes of people who fled the dictatorship. The aim is to help outsiders grasp the hardships of North Korean citizens and the walls that stand between them and the wider world."
      },
      {
        title: "A caste system underpins life in the North",
        text: "When the three-year Korean War ended, Kim Il-sung declared himself president and built a communist state. His rule rested on a balance of rewards and penalties. He gave special privileges to those he saw as loyal and punished anyone he suspected of disloyalty with a heavy hand. The tool he used was a caste system that sorted the population into three layers.\n\nThe core class sat at the top of the social pyramid. It included senior military officers, party members, and people who had proven their loyalty to Kim Il-sung during the civil war. Most of them lived in the capital.\n\nThe wavering class held people with good records who might still turn against the state. Members included Koreans who had come back from Japan and former members of the core class.\n\nThe hostile class included religious believers, Koreans with past ties to the south, and political suspects. Anyone convicted of a political crime from the core or wavering classes also dropped down here. Members of this group needed special permission to enter the capital, and they were barred from living in the better farmland of the south.\n\nYour caste decided where you could live, how much schooling you and your children could reach for, and what jobs you could hold. Children inherited their parents' caste. There was no ladder to climb. You could only stay where you were or slide down.\n\nCaste also shaped what you could eat. Food came from state distribution centers. You handed over money, and the government issued coupons for staples. Money alone did not get you far. Each caste had a minimum ration set for its members. To this day, most North Koreans do not even know that the caste system exists by name, since contact between groups is so thin. Suspicion runs deep as people bump into discrimination and dead ends in education and work.\n\nThe way any society splits its classes reflects how its wealth is shared."
      },
      {
        title: "The Juche doctrine keeps the regime in power",
        text: "When Kim Il-sung set up the communist state, he dreamed of a North Korea that stood on its own feet. To make that dream real, he poured the Juche philosophy into the minds of his citizens. The teaching said that only strong people could carry the banner of communism, and that North Korea could survive without foreign help if its people paid the price.\n\nJuche lessons showed up in speeches and study sessions that everyone had to attend. Factory workers lost work hours to these lectures. They also had to write essays proving they had taken the lessons to heart. Juche also carried a strong cult of the leader, and the people were told to worship him. Any country that had given up communism was labelled a nation of weak citizens. North Korean propaganda pointed at South Korea as proof, calling it a country that had chosen democracy and a tight bond with the United States.\n\nOnce a belief system justifies tyranny, people learn to live with it.\n\nCitizens were pushed to watch their neighbors and report anything suspicious to the authorities, which turned nearly everyone into a quiet spy for the state. The press loved to print stories of children turning in their own parents as proof of devotion. Suspicious acts included staying overnight at a relative's home without a permit, cooking on a hot plate, using a rice cooker, lighting a bulb stronger than forty watts, or burning through too much electricity.\n\nFamilies were grouped into units called inminban. The leader of each unit, usually an older woman, had a government handler she could report to about odd speech, movements, or behavior. The state also set up a patrol group called the kyuch'aldae, which had the right to barge into homes without warning, search for contraband, and arrest anyone who broke the rules. Fear spread so wide that no one dared speak out. In time, Kim Il-sung controlled the whole country.\n\nUnlike students in other communist states, North Korean students and intellectuals never dared to protest, as Barbara Demick notes."
      },
      {
        title: "Kim Il-sung wanted to be worshipped like a god",
        text: "Kim Il-sung wanted to be the only voice in his people's lives, so he banned Christianity and other religions. He cast himself as a godlike figure and his son, Kim Jong-il, as a Christ-like one. He hoped to spark awe and build a cult by borrowing the language of faith. Worship of the leader grew almost on its own, woven into newspapers, books, and songs that everyone absorbed without question. The state's media was his main tool. The press told stories about him and his son. One claim was that singing songs about Kim Il-sung could calm a stormy sea. Another held that the birth of Kim Jong-il had lit a bright star and a double rainbow in the sky.\n\nEvery home and office had to keep portraits of Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-il on the wall. Public buildings did too, and the size of the portraits grew with the size of the room. The press praised citizens who had risked their lives to rescue the leaders' portraits from burning buildings. Children never got to celebrate their own birthdays. Each year on April 15 and February 16, the birthdays of the two leaders, they thanked the nation's fathers for the welfare they provided.\n\nLeader birthdays were some of the few bright spots of the year. People could get meat and electricity, rare treats in daily North Korean life.\n\nThe cult grew so wide that both leaders were hailed as experts in every field. They would occasionally visit factories, offices, and farms and offer tips on the spot. The state treated those comments as expert advice and tried to put them into practice.\n\nThe peak of the cult came with the ten days of mourning for Kim Il-sung. He died of a heart attack on July 9, 1994. Thousands gathered at his statues and tried to outdo each other in their grief, wailing and even banging their heads against the walls. Anyone who could not produce tears feared for their safety. The state banned all entertainment during those ten days. A similar wave of mourning followed Kim Jong-il's death on December 17, 2011."
      },
      {
        title: "The fall of the USSR dragged North Korea down with it",
        text: "North Korea's economy leaned hard on its communist neighbors. Outwardly, Kim Il-sung kept preaching self-reliance. Inwardly, the country ran on cheap oil, electricity, and factory equipment shipped in from the USSR, China, and other allies. When the USSR collapsed in 1991, North Korea's economy sank with it. Its factories could not run, and there was nothing to sell abroad.\n\nThe state owed piles of debt to China and Russia. When the loans went unpaid, both countries cut off raw materials. The loss of power and fuel hit the population hard. The state rationed electricity down to almost nothing. Homes lost heating and running water. Many North Koreans died of cold and the illnesses that followed. The power shortage also broke the harvest, since farms depended on machinery and modern methods, and the country of nearly twenty-three million people ran out of food.\n\nThe more there was to complain about, the more important it was to make sure no one did, as Barbara Demick put it.\n\nForeign donors refused to step in. They felt the government had to fix its priorities first. A global panic broke out in March 1993 when North Korea pulled out of the treaty that stopped the spread of nuclear weapons. Many feared that a North Korean bomb could start a war, since the state poured huge sums into its military. The armed forces numbered about a million soldiers, an enormous army for a country its size.\n\nThe United States tried to trade energy aid for a freeze on the nuclear program, but the deal fell apart. North Korea did not stick to its side of the bargain. The people did not blame their own leaders for the darkness and hunger. They blamed the United States and the sanctions.\n\nThe state kept funding its nuclear program while its own people went without light and food.\n\nA telling detail of daily life: in Pyongyang at night, it is almost impossible to tell one building from another, because the city is so dark."
      },
      {
        title: "Black markets filled the gap left by empty food centers",
        text: "The breakdown of the factories hit the economy hard, and a string of poor harvests finally broke its back. The state slid into a deep nutrition crisis. Once the distribution centers stopped stocking food, the country began a massive scramble for anything edible. Selling food and other goods went against the spirit of communism, and the authorities called it an economic crime. Kim Il-sung eased the rules so people could sell homegrown vegetables. That small opening did not solve anything, and people began to trade much more than vegetables.\n\nAs the official food network collapsed, the black market grew. People turned to illegal trade to keep themselves fed. Tofu, noodles, and kimchi were easy to find. Rice was rare because Kim Il-sung had banned the sale of grain. In 1997, the state made selling grain a capital offense. Ordinary people fell back on cornmeal as a substitute for rice.\n\nThe people swallowed their fate and never questioned the leadership. Each new hardship brought a fresh theory from the propaganda machine, designed to explain why the state could not share more. Officials claimed that food had to be held back so that on the day of reunification, the North could feed South Koreans who had been starving for years. On other days, the state blamed the United States and the sanctions for the famine.\n\nThe hunger became a strange badge of patriotism, tied to devotion to the country.\n\nPeople started selling their homes when they could no longer pay the steep prices on the illegal food market. A black market in real estate rose up, where citizens swapped houses to survive.\n\nSoon, families that had once lived in comfortable homes were out on the streets. They slept in train stations and begged for food, and many died of starvation. By the time Kim Jong-il took over after his father's death in 1994, the famine had already taken millions of lives."
      },
      {
        title: "Defection was the only way out for the desperate",
        text: "In North Korea, the pace of defection sped up after the famine. Before then, those who left were mainly diplomats sent abroad on official trips. Once that trickle turned into a stream, the state began holding the relatives of those diplomats hostage at home, to make sure the envoys came back to their families.\n\nEven knowing that defection was a capital crime did not stop people from trying to reach the South. Most saw it as a better option than the hunger and homelessness at home. The route out ran through the northeastern Chinese border and across two rivers. The coast was fenced off, so boats were useless. The defectors had to cross on foot. Some who could not walk paid others to carry them across.\n\nOn the far side, they waited for guards to look away or bribed the ones on duty. Some hired brokers who planned the trip and handled the bribes. These smugglers also arranged fresh clothes, a place to sleep, food, and sometimes travel papers. A broker might line up a passport, often stolen and altered, and book a flight from China to South Korea for the right price. Anyone caught defecting or working as a broker faced severe punishment, including execution.\n\nThe hope of a better life on the other side pushed people to take the deadly risk.\n\nBrokers also bought wives for unmarried Chinese men, and many North Korean women accepted the deal. More than half of the 100,000 North Koreans living in China were women, often enslaved and poorly treated by their new husbands.\n\nOther smugglers moved Chinese electronics and DVDs into North Korea. When no one was watching, North Koreans secretly watched South Korean soap operas. The shows pulled them in. The actors spoke the same language and looked like them. People could see how others lived abroad, and the boldest wanted to see with their own eyes if it was real."
      },
      {
        title: "Final thoughts",
        text: "For years, outside experts kept predicting that the North Korean regime would collapse. Against all odds, it survived. It outlived the fall of the Soviet Union, the death of Kim Il-sung, and the fall of the Berlin Wall. The state clings to its policy of militarism, building up arms and testing nuclear weapons in the open. In the leader's view, the world is full of enemies that threaten the country's safety. The economy is held back by weak and baseless reforms. In one strange rule, only women over forty are allowed to sell their own products. Everyone else has to work in state factories for small pay, and that is the best-case scenario. Some factories cannot even pay their workers at all.\n\nIt is easy for outsiders who have never lived under tyranny to judge North Koreans for putting up with a dictator. In truth, those who live under the regime have no real choice. They have no access to decent schools or to outside media that could show them a different life behind the wall that separates their country from the rest of the world. With constant propaganda, they only grow more attached to the life the state has built around them.\n\nFor anyone planning to visit, the country does have a small number of tourist sites that draw visitors. A few simple tips help. You will be assigned a guide, and it is wise to keep them in sight at all times for your own safety. Stay inside the official tourism areas. Be ready to stay off social media and the internet for the whole visit. Following these rules helps keep a strange and tightly watched trip on track."
      }
    ]
  },
  "notorious-rbg.json": {
    base: { id: "notorious-rbg", title: "Notorious RBG", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781681248803 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Anger is a waste of your hours",
        text: "A nation's history never runs in a straight line, and it is shaped by complicated people. If you had met Ruth Bader Ginsburg, known as RBG, in her younger years or later on, you might not have given her a second look. She never tried to stand out and kept to herself. Yet this quiet woman made history many times over. Only the second woman ever nominated to the Supreme Court, she argued and won several women's rights cases before the bench. One unfair case at a time, she laid the groundwork for the more equal society we live in today. Each step forward was a hard-won gain, but those obstacles never stopped her. Her principles guided her through every fight.\n\nThe arc of the moral universe is long, but it bends toward justice, as Ruth Bader Ginsburg said.\n\nHer mother's advice also helped her along the way. Anger is never worth the time it costs. She learned to accept the range of views and personalities around her and to work toward fair compromises.\n\nResentment, anger, and other heavy feelings are never useful. They just burn up time and energy.\n\nRuth Bader Ginsburg was not only an expert in her field. She was, first and foremost, a kind and caring person. Those personal qualities were what made her such a fair and professional judge. She was reserved, took her time, and chose every word with care.\n\nThis short summary will help you rediscover RBG by sketching a full picture of an outstanding person, both in her work and in her character. We will walk through her hard road to the Supreme Court and the qualities that made it possible."
      },
      {
        title: "Blocking out the noise and pushing through",
        text: "As a young Jewish girl from Brooklyn, Ruth Bader Ginsburg attended James Madison High School and graduated in 1950. No one in those classrooms could have predicted that quiet Ruth would grow up to be a Supreme Court Justice. That kind of role was thought to be for boys.\n\nRuth read Greek and Norse myths and the adventures of the fearless Nancy Drew. Her childhood was happy, thanks to her strict but loving mother, Celia Amster. When Celia fell gravely ill, RBG worked and studied harder than ever to make her proud. It paid off. She graduated with honors and went on to Cornell University. She never made it to her high school graduation, because her mother died only days before. That loss did not slow her down. It drove her to become the accomplished woman her mother could have been if society had given her the chance.\n\nAt Cornell, RBG majored in Government and took an undergraduate class in Constitutional Law. That class lit the spark for her life's work in law.\n\nCornell also gave her something else. She met a fellow student, Marty Ginsburg, and married him in 1954. He became her partner and supporter for life. Together they headed to Harvard Law School. While there, RBG picked up another key lesson, this time from her mother-in-law. She advised her to pretend to be a little hard of hearing and to tune out the cruel things people said. That skill helped RBG at Cornell, at Harvard, and later at Fort Sill. Women in law programs were rare, and the few who were there often hid how sharp they were. RBG did the same for a while. At Harvard, she was one of only two women on the Law Review, a student-run journal of legal scholarship. That was a rare honor at the time.\n\nSometimes it is smarter to ignore unkind people. That way, they cannot steal your peace.\n\nAs a student, RBG ran into shocking levels of sex discrimination. She was once told she could not enter a reading room that was reserved for men. She was barred from the Annual Law Review Banquet because it was a boys-only event. Perhaps the worst sign of all was that the main exam building did not have a women's restroom. None of this angered or scared her. She just kept working."
      },
      {
        title: "Grit and steady nerves carry you to the top",
        text: "Before Harvard, RBG and Marty spent two years at the Fort Sill army base after Marty was called up to active duty. While there, RBG sat the civil service exam for a federal job, but the offer vanished once the panel learned she was three months pregnant. The wall of rules she hit at Fort Sill lit a new fire in her. When she came back, she studied with a young child at home. On top of that, Marty was diagnosed with testicular cancer, so for a long stretch, RBG was reading briefs and grading papers for two people at once.\n\nAfter finishing near the top of her class, RBG had a few strong offers on the table. Her Harvard mentor, Professor Al Sacks, put her name forward for a clerkship with Supreme Court Justice Frankfurter. Frankfurter had never rejected a Sacks pick before. RBG broke that streak, and she figured she had three marks against her. She was a woman, a Jew, and a mother.\n\nJob hunting was a maze. Many interview sign-up sheets had men only at the top.\n\nA break came when Gerald Gunther, a professor at Columbia Law School who valued her mind and her work ethic, lined up a District Court clerkship for her. RBG threw herself into the role under Federal Judge Edmund L. Palmieri of the Southern District of New York. Not long after, an unusual chance landed in her lap, an invitation to co-write a book on Swedish civil procedure. RBG kissed her husband and daughter goodbye for a while and moved across the Atlantic. That stretch of independence stayed with her forever, because it let her stand on her own two feet and showed her a world where women had more say in their own lives."
      },
      {
        title: "Equality for women needs strong men",
        text: "A year before her first Supreme Court argument, RBG and a small group of like-minded colleagues set up the ACLU's Women's Rights Project. Through that work, RBG got her hands on the case of Frontiero v. Richardson and brought it to the Supreme Court. In the case, she argued that benefits given to military service members' spouses could not be handed out differently based on the gender of the service member.\n\nUsually quiet and unsure of herself, RBG shifted gears during her oral argument. She came across as confident, clear, and persuasive. She knew the case better than the judges did, and it showed. She spoke for nearly ten minutes without interruption. Her careful arguments and well-chosen analogies won the day.\n\nOnce she started volunteering for the ACLU, RBG received a flood of letters from women dealing with everyday sex discrimination. One woman had been discharged from the military because she was pregnant. Another was kept off the varsity team even though she was the best tennis player at her university. Another was turned away from Princeton's summer engineering program, all because of gender. The examples kept piling up.\n\nTo RBG's surprise, many female law students did more than complain. They started fighting for their rights. Things began to change, and in the middle of that change, RBG was asked to teach the first-ever class on women in law.\n\nAround that time, RBG realized she could no longer stay silent. Quiet acceptance was no longer an option. She and her female colleagues filed a federal pay-discrimination claim against the university where she worked. They won. From then on, she was a regular at the Supreme Court, fighting case after case for equality and an end to discrimination.\n\nReal, lasting change in our society happens slowly, one step at a time.\n\nRBG worked tactically. She introduced one careful logical step at a time so the court could keep up. She believed that pushing too fast would wreck the progress she had made.\n\nIt is worth noting that RBG never once argued that women deserved special treatment or that they were better than men. Her case was for equal treatment on both sides. She wanted a world where men and women could each reach their full potential as human beings."
      },
      {
        title: "A good marriage is a partnership that runs both ways",
        text: "Marty Ginsburg never minded living in the shadow of his famous wife. For one thing, he was highly successful in his own field. For another, his support for RBG was unconditional and genuine. One could argue that more than fifty years of a happy marriage, full of warmth and steady romance, is as much of an achievement as breaking through a glass ceiling.\n\nMarty and Ruth adored each other, and that love let them chase their own dreams without giving up on family life. Friends of the couple often pointed out how similar yet different they were. Where RBG was serious and quiet, Marty was playful and funny. He brought out a side of her that no one else could.\n\nFor RBG, her marriage was a model of mutual respect and equality between men and women. No matter how rough the legal world was to her, she always got first-class treatment at home.\n\nA strong marriage lets both partners keep their independence while sharing life and goals side by side.\n\nThat kind of marriage was rare for her generation. Marty, even though he did not seek the spotlight, became a quiet role model for men ready to change. He was selfless, loving, and respectful of his wife's choices, far from the old stereotypes of toxic masculinity. When he spoke about his relationship with RBG, he said their mutual support from the start had never been a sacrifice. It was simply part of how their family worked."
      },
      {
        title: "Welcome views that differ from your own",
        text: "It is hard to imagine what was going through RBG's mind when the Oval Office called, after she had nearly given up hope of being nominated to the Supreme Court. Was she scared? Maybe excited? Nervous? Later, she joked that she felt like a bride. All eyes were on her, and she was about to start a unique and exciting journey.\n\nEven though the list of possible nominees was long, on June 14, 1993, the day President Bill Clinton announced that RBG was his pick, no one could miss the certainty in his voice. He called her a legal star and a hero of the women's movement, a moderate centrist with strong morals.\n\nRuth Bader Ginsburg cannot be called a liberal or a conservative. She has proved herself too thoughtful for such simple labels, as Bill Clinton said.\n\nRBG's appointment to the Supreme Court raised the visibility of women's talents across society.\n\nOn the Court, RBG was as steady and rational as ever. She looked for compromise and never let politics or personal views get in the way of her relationships with the other Justices.\n\nEven though sex discrimination was no longer as common as it once was, it was still a huge problem, and RBG now had to fight it in a very different way.\n\nAs a Justice, Ruth Bader Ginsburg never forgot her principles. She wrote sharp, powerful dissents. When two more women joined the Court during the Obama administration, she did all she could to help them feel safe and confident.\n\nA surprising note from her life: RBG's closest friend on the bench was Justice Scalia, whose views were as far from hers as you could get."
      },
      {
        title: "Final thoughts",
        text: "In her later years, after the painful loss of her husband Marty to cancer in 2010, RBG never lost heart. She kept looking for the joy in life and kept working. The progress she had fought for was real, but the struggle was not over. Today, much of what RBG fought for is still at risk. To honor her life's work and her priceless legacy, we have to keep doing what Ruth Bader Ginsburg started.\n\nRuth Bader Ginsburg is a fine example of a modern hero who fights with carefully chosen words and sharp thinking, not with her fists. After facing discrimination herself, she spent her whole life challenging injustice and making the country fairer for everyone. Much like her mother was taken from her too early, RBG was taken from us while society still needed her wisdom and strong principles. Justice Ginsburg died in 2020 at the age of 87 from cancer. That is exactly why it falls on us now to challenge the inequalities that remain and keep fighting discrimination.\n\nTo live a little more like RBG, keep her fight for equality and fair justice alive in your own corner of the world. Always pick your battles, since anger gets in the way, so choose the fights that are truly worth your time and energy. Do not burn bridges. The fight for what is right cannot be won alone, so be the kind of leader who pulls others in. And invest time in your marriage, since a healthy romantic relationship can give you real support in your work and your growth as a person."
      }
    ]
  },
  "nudge.json": {
    base: { id: "nudge", title: "Nudge", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781681346261 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Nudges hide in plain sight",
        text: "A nudge is any factor that has a strong pull on what people do. Choice architects use nudges to shift someone's decision without taking any options off the table.\n\nNudges work on real people, a species that makes predictable mistakes, but they would slide right off Econs, an imaginary species that never gets things wrong in a predictable way.\n\nRational Econs react to incentives, so if the government taxes candy, they buy less of it. They do not care about rewards and shrugs, which they treat as background noise. Incentives do shape human behavior to some degree, but the small nudges around us often do the heaviest lifting.\n\nNudges live inside nearly every decision we make.\n\nWith the right mix of incentives and nudges, we can improve other people's lives and tackle big social problems while still respecting each person's freedom to choose.\n\nWant to learn more? Keep reading to unlock the power of Nudge Theory and add something useful to the well-being of the people around you."
      },
      {
        title: "Choice architecture is everywhere",
        text: "A choice architect's main job is to shape the setting in which people make decisions. Many people are choice architects without knowing it. You are probably one, too, whether you design ballots that help voters pick candidates, prescribe treatment options as a doctor, plan a city's layout, run a restaurant, or raise a child you care deeply about.\n\nTake a moment to think about your own role as a choice architect. Are you setting up your life to match your goals and values? Are you making thoughtful choices about saving, retirement, and other big parts of your future? It is time to get serious and put your life in order, one decision at a time.\n\nRespect for individual choice is a cornerstone of a free and peaceful society.\n\nLike architects who design apartment buildings, choice architects arrange options to shape the choices we make. Their job is to nudge. Choice architecture has a lot in common with regular architecture. One key parallel is that there is no such thing as a fully neutral design.\n\nWhen an architect designs a new school, for example, they get a list of rules and limits to work within. These can be legal, aesthetic, and practical. The architect has to sweat the details, because small choices can change a lot. In the same way, small details can change how people behave. The safer bet is to assume that everything matters.\n\nIf you shape the choices other people make, you are a choice architect, as Richard H. Thaler and Cass R. Sunstein put it.\n\nLibertarian paternalism is a common phrase in this field. It sounds like a contradiction, but it has a clear meaning. When libertarian modifies paternalism, it means choice architects can protect freedom of choice while gently guiding people toward better outcomes. People should still have the freedom to do as they like and to opt out of arrangements they do not want."
      },
      {
        title: "Your decisions follow patterns",
        text: "Nudges come into play when people face a situation too complex to fully take in. In choice architecture, nudges shape behavior in predictable ways without changing economic incentives, and they are never mandatory. Putting healthy snacks at the cash register counts as a nudge, while banning junk food does not.\n\nPeople need guidance to navigate tough choices well.\n\nEmployers are important choice architects. They give useful nudges to their workers, like health benefits and retirement plans. The idea of a company aiming for both profit and positive impact is appealing. It is a win-win where the business can do well financially and help the environment at the same time, for example by using nudges that cut air pollution. That fits with the broader ideas of corporate social responsibility and sustainable business practices.\n\nIf you want a well-designed choice environment, it helps to keep four ideas in mind.\n\nFirst, difficulty level. Tying shoes is a skill most people master by age six. Life often throws harder problems at us. Technology helps with some of them, but others stay out of reach.\n\nSecond, frequency. Even hard problems get easier with practice. Yet some of the most important decisions in life leave little room to rehearse.\n\nThird, feedback. Practice helps when people get good feedback, and people only learn when that feedback is quick and clear. Some situations do not give that kind of feedback. Nudges fill the gap.\n\nFourth, knowing what you want. Many people cannot predict how today's choices will shape tomorrow's life. Too many options, with no one to talk them through, often do more harm than good. A gentle nudge can be a relief in those moments.\n\nA 2018 study by HUI Research and Soundtrack Your Brand found that the background music in a restaurant can quietly shape the dining experience, a small sign of how minor details carry real weight."
      },
      {
        title: "We all slip up sometimes",
        text: "It is built into human nature to make the wrong call at times, and a few patterns explain why.\n\nDefault option. People love the default option because it feels safe, trusted, and easy. It is usually more convenient to stick with what is already chosen than to hunt for a different one. A well-chosen default can lead to big wins, from more savings to better health.\n\nPath of least resistance. People like the easy road because it takes less effort. The default is often that easy road, and it is not always the best one.\n\nHeuristics. Mental shortcuts like anchoring, availability, representativeness, overconfidence, and loss aversion often steer us away from the best call.\n\nThe illusion of randomness. Sometimes we read meaning into patterns that are just chance, and then we make bad calls based on that false meaning.\n\nMental accounting. We often make poor financial decisions. Our habits around spending, saving, and investing can be far from optimal, dragged down by cognitive biases and emotions.\n\nMindless choosing. Picking at random can ease the stress of a decision, but the fallout can still be huge. The trick is to balance making things easy with making them smart.\n\nIn short, people lean on simple shortcuts to decide, and those shortcuts sometimes lead them down the wrong path. We are often too busy to weigh the alternatives, so we take what comes and end up easily swayed, even on the biggest choices of life. That is something traditional economics has missed.\n\nMindless choices push people toward bad outcomes, especially when self-control is weak.\n\nStill, the same tendency can be used for good. In Chicago, the city found a clever fix for a stretch of Lake Shore Drive where drivers kept ignoring dangerous curves. Workers tightened the white lane stripes in the riskiest spots, and the visual cue alone slowed drivers down. Nudges work because they are quiet and they help people move past biases that would otherwise pull them off course."
      },
      {
        title: "Take charge of how you decide",
        text: "Mandatory rules can feel heavy and push people into corners. Nudges offer a softer and often more effective way to guide decisions. Skilled choice architects help people make the best call without taking choices away. Here are six principles of good choice architecture.\n\nMotivating incentives. Companies should think hard about what drives their design choices and make sure the incentives match what people care about. That means weighing the needs of the people who will use the product, alongside budgets and goals.\n\nClarifying mappings. Decisions range from simple to muddy. Good mappings turn messy decisions into a clear path toward the right call.\n\nThoughtful defaults. Standard options help people who do not want to make an active choice. If the default is sloppy, people end up frustrated. Forcing people to choose is not the answer either, since some will see it as a chore even if it boosts freedom. A strong default is what matters.\n\nValuable feedback. Steady feedback drives good performance. Well-designed systems always tell you when you are on track and when you are slipping, even if you do not notice it. A famous example is the timely warning that something is about to go wrong.\n\nAnticipating errors. Mistakes are part of being human, and there is no exception. Think about birth control pills in blister packs with numbered slots. Even during the placebo week, the packaging teaches you to keep the habit. Good design knows our flaws and uses them in our favor.\n\nStructuring complex choices. A clear structure breaks a hard problem into parts that are easy to weigh. It also gives a reliable, flexible framework, which leads to better outcomes.\n\nWhen applied well, these nudges help people facing complex choices land on better answers. In personal finance, setting up automatic contributions to a retirement fund is a nudge that simplifies a long-term decision, respects freedom, and improves a person's finances without overwhelming them.\n\nGuide people rather than decide for them."
      },
      {
        title: "Small nudges can reshape a society",
        text: "Many companies use quiet, indirect tricks to nudge people into spending more, even when it cuts against their own interests. They might set defaults that favor the seller, hide fees, and push prices up. The point is to balance corporate interests with consumer well-being. The sale of extended warranties is one common example. Still, nudges are not only for manipulation. Governments and public institutions have started using them to shape citizens' behavior in ways that lift the common good.\n\nThe fate of any group is tied to the shared knowledge and choices of its members.\n\nOne powerful way to shape behavior is to tell people what others are doing. People tend to copy their peers, so sharing positive social norms can drive change. Telling taxpayers that most of their neighbors pay their taxes on time, for example, can lift tax compliance.\n\nOn the flip side, people often overestimate how much others drink, partly because of media coverage. Correcting that misperception through social norms campaigns can pull behavior in a healthier direction.\n\nSubtle cues, sometimes called primes, also nudge behavior. Asking people about their intentions to do something makes them more likely to follow through. Visible objects and scents can quietly shape choices too.\n\nThe more choices you give people, the more help you need to provide, as Richard H. Thaler and Cass R. Sunstein note.\n\nIn the end, governments and large institutions can use the power of social influence to encourage better behavior. They can frame messages positively, correct misperceptions, and add subtle cues, making life easier for themselves and for the public."
      },
      {
        title: "Final thoughts",
        text: "Nudges matter in many of life's biggest areas, from savings and social security to credit markets, healthcare, environmental policy, marriage, and more. There is almost no end to where they can reach.\n\nThat is why it pays to understand choice architecture and the new ways it offers to lift human well-being. What is striking is that anyone can step into the role of a choice architect. It is not reserved for experts or officials. Each of us can shape the choices that surround us and the people around us. When we take that on, we open up a future filled with chances to grow and to thrive.\n\nA few simple habits to try. Accept that being wrong sometimes is part of growing. Put your long-term goals ahead of short-term pulls. And use tools like automatic contributions to build a secure retirement you can count on."
      }
    ]
  },
  "on-writing.json": {
    base: { id: "on-writing", title: "On Writing", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781636612042 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Writing is how we pass on complex feelings and ideas",
        text: "As a way to communicate, writing has been around for a long time. It has also been our way of recording events. Writing is woven into human life and still plays its part in society today. At its heart, writing is a way of carrying language and feeling through marks and symbols on a page or screen.\n\nWriting is more than a way to send messages. It can carry feelings that plain words would hide.\n\nWriting is a powerful tool. It links a writer to readers no matter how many times they read the same story. The creative side of writing is usually called literary writing. It is the making of new literary work, including poetry, novels, short stories, and more. Pulling those works together is part of the writing process too. Through literary writing, a writer can pass on feelings while telling a story the reader can relate to.\n\nA good writer has to be a strong storyteller and reach the reader as the story moves forward.\n\nThere is real skill and training behind good writing, yet it is also easy enough to start without a long list of qualifications. That is not a knock on education. It is a nod to the gift of writing itself. Stephen King is a fine example. He earned his English degree, but he was already a talented writer, penning articles before he turned sixteen.\n\nA good writer writes. A great writer reads the work of other writers.\n\nKing insists that everyone has some writing talent and can grow into a strong writer with practice and training. Many self-taught writers today prove the point. King was a hungry reader growing up. He always had his nose in a book. That habit fed his need to write stories of his own.\n\nIn the chapters ahead, you will get useful insight into the craft of writing, the traps to avoid, and how to come out on top. King brings the big ideas and goals of writing into the open and shows how to find inspiration that lasts."
      },
      {
        title: "Build and stick to a steady writing schedule",
        text: "Writing is more than the act of lining up words. It is deeper than that, and it calls for seriousness from the writer. Writing is an art, on par with ballet or synchronized swimming. The harmony of those arts comes from one thing, practice. Without practice, there is no art.\n\nWriting is an art, and like any art, it takes discipline and dedication to do well.\n\nNo matter how talented a writer is, they will stay stuck in the middle if they never practice. Some people treat writing as something you can just walk up and do without warming up. Even better work leans on a stockpile of knowledge in the brain. The rule holds for writing too. The more you practice, the sharper your creative process becomes.\n\nWithout practice, mastery is out of reach. If you want to be good at writing, you must practice.\n\nSo how often should a new writer work if they want to get somewhere? The answer is simple. Write at every chance. Writing is like breathing. If a writer wants to live, they must write. That habit keeps stories turning over in the writer's head, ready to be set down. Look at writing like a sport, and you see that athletes have to drill their moves again and again.\n\nWriting is a craft, and every craft has techniques and rules. A gift is only sharpened through doing. New writers often want to take classes first, watch someone else break down the craft, and only then sit down to write. That is not always the best path. Aristotle put it well. We learn the things we have to learn before we can do them by doing them.\n\nA good writer keeps showing up to sharpen the craft.\n\nWriters can build a schedule that centers the mind and sharpens focus. King suggests writing every day. That kind of routine trains the brain to get more productive with each session.\n\nA small note about King's life. His house is now a tourist attraction."
      },
      {
        title: "The place where you write shapes the work",
        text: "While it is important to write freely and often, the place where the writing happens matters too. The scene you choose to sit in can shape the writing itself. It can even act as a spark. King offers a quick test. Put your desk in a corner, and every time you sit down there to write, ask yourself why it is not in the middle of the room. Life is not a support system for art. It is the other way around.\n\nPicking where to write is as important as writing itself. It frames the mind.\n\nThat line is a reminder to lean on art for comfort when life is hard. It also pushes you to ask honest questions about your life. Do you want it? Can it be better? Can you find a way forward? That kind of thinking narrows your focus to one thing and lets you build from there.\n\nFind a space that calms you and stretches your thinking.\n\nThere is also the old line that life imitates art, meaning much of what we live shows up in art first. By that logic, writing should mirror our world or a world we imagine. The setting you write in, whether a room in your head or a real desk by the window, plays a big role in what you produce. If you want unfiltered creativity, pick a place or a mood that pushes your mind into overdrive.\n\nYour surroundings and your situation shape your writing more than you think.\n\nSometimes you do not get to pick. Life hands you the setting through its own wild design. For King, the urge to escape poverty forced him into a creative surge. He was determined to build a better life for himself and his family. That kind of inspiration is common, and it can be very reliable. The state of your life can be the corner table you keep returning to in your mind.\n\nKing himself prefers to write on paper with a fountain pen."
      },
      {
        title: "Knowing how to write makes the work easier",
        text: "There are many pieces to writing, and each one matters. But while time and place are important, they do not help much if you do not know how to write. King's work speaks for itself, which makes him a trusted teacher of the craft.\n\nKnowing when to write is only half the battle. Knowing how to write is the foundation.\n\nIn what most people expected to be a memoir, King slips in plenty of advice for writers who want to follow his path. Ask any professional and they will tell you that knowing how to do something is the first step to getting good at it. Once the steps become a habit, the results often speak for themselves.\n\nFor any craft to run well, there have to be guidelines to lead the practitioner.\n\nKing lays out a lot of advice for writers. A few tips stand out. Do not pad your sentences with long words just to sound smart. The best words are the simple ones. The first word that comes to mind when you write is often the right one. Pair your nouns with strong verbs, since the noun-verb structure carries writing. Avoid passive verbs and lean on active ones. Treat adverbs like a tricky friend. Use them lightly. Read and write a lot. There is no real shortcut. When you read, pay attention to the bad books too. They show you what to avoid or fix. When you start a project, see it through. Do not take breaks until you are done. And when you use description, make sure it lands for the reader as clearly as it did for you, or even more so.\n\nWhen you write, keep a clear filter for what matters and what only sounds good.\n\nA few more tips from King. A strong piece of fiction starts with a story before a theme shows up, not the other way around, so do not lock yourself in by picking a theme first. Writing is about touching lives and sparking dreams, not about making money.\n\nAmateurs sit and wait for inspiration. The rest of us just get up and go to work, as Stephen King puts it."
      },
      {
        title: "Your reader plays a big part in the work",
        text: "Art exists to be enjoyed, taken in, and shared. Without an audience, art loses its value. For writers, without readers, they write into the wind. As you create, you have to think about the people who will receive the work. The target audience is part of the whole process and forms the base of any fanbase. Without readers, there is no point in writing. Art is meant to be appreciated.\n\nYour work has to be shaped for the audience you want to reach.\n\nIf you want to reach a specific group, your work needs one central theme that appeals to a certain kind of reader or moment. That makes it easier to know what you are writing for and who you are writing to. Single-theme writing is a safe approach and helps you carve out a niche, but it can also feel limiting over time. King suggests choosing a story first and weaving a theme into it to avoid that trap.\n\nSticking to one theme or style can feel narrow. Only pick that path if you want to reach a specific group.\n\nEven when you aim at one group, a strong work will draw in curious readers outside it. Since the audience can shape the art, it can pay to stick with the style or theme you are known for, so you do not push your core fans away. Losing your fanbase means fewer sales and a colder reception for anything you put out next.\n\nYour word choices should fit the audience you want, so you do not lose them.\n\nKnowing your audience also shapes the tone and language you use. As mentioned earlier, King thinks fancy words and phrases are pointless if they get in the way of clear communication. The simplest rule is to keep it as clear as possible, so the reader does not get worn out. Communication is the heart of writing, and it has to be done well.\n\nDescription begins in the writer's imagination but should finish in the reader's, as Stephen King says."
      },
      {
        title: "Write for readers, not for shallow rewards",
        text: "Many people think writing is a path to get rich, find fame, or attract admirers. King knows those are the distractions that fill the head of a new writer dreaming of sudden stardom. Some writers believe writing will fix their money problems. Others want to fly around the world signing books and meeting fans.\n\nFind the right reasons to make art that lasts.\n\nKing argues that these are the wrong reasons to write. He calls them shallow and empty. So why should we write at all? There has to be a reason to write that does not fade with time. The reason should be rooted in things that are timeless and unaffected by trends. As an artist, your goal should be to make work that still matters long after it was released.\n\nThe reason to write should be to inspire and move readers, not just to chase a quick payout.\n\nWriting is not about money. Money will follow if the work is good. If you write only for money, you will end up forcing a style or stretching a story to squeeze out more profit. The lure of money can hijack the creative process and damage the quality of the work. Writers who fall into that trap produce what critics call cash grabs, books made only for the money and not for the art.\n\nWrite to lift the lives of your readers. Move them to feel more and do more.\n\nIn the end, writing is mostly about a few things. It is about enriching the lives of the people who read your work, so they can change lives of their own. It is about deepening your own life, not in money but in the way art shapes and refines you. It is about getting up, staying up, and pushing through, because writing is a long road of self-discovery and growth. And it is about creating happiness, in others and in yourself, the way all art does."
      },
      {
        title: "Final thoughts",
        text: "Writing is one of humanity's oldest ways to share what we feel. It has carried the most complicated feelings from one person to another. As an art, it still does that today and lets an author pass a message to readers without losing it along the way. Yet to master the art of writing, you only need two things, reading and writing.\n\nA lot of reading and writing goes into becoming a writer. You start by reading the work of writers who have more experience. That sharpens your mind and builds the hunger to write stories of your own. Practice is just as important. Steady writing drills are the surest way to gain mastery. And to make practice count, you need a strict schedule. That creates a system and grows discipline.\n\nIf you want to write better, pay attention to where you write. The scene around you can lift the work or hold it back. Every art form has its rules, and writing is no different. To learn how to write well, you have to follow them.\n\nFinally, know your readers and write to them in words they can understand. Reaching for big words just to sound deep is lazy and shows a lack of craft. As an artist, your job is to touch lives with your work. Let that be the fire that drives you when you sit down to write.\n\nA simple exercise to try. Write a piece of any kind. Start small, then add pages as you go, as long as the new material does not break the thread of the story."
      }
    ]
  }
};
